<br>
The other side of the coin is if you're the leader type, you need to find people to put together a group.  This means you want to know: what classes are available, where they are, and who they are so you can send out your invites.  If you're a raiding guild, a non-anon non-role rule is absolutely essential.  The raid leader needs to be able to find out quickly how many clerics are online, any mages, any shaman, who are my available trackers to let me know what our potential targets are, etc. etc..  If people are hiding, the raid leader can't get answers to these questions and that means no raids.<br>
<br>
Notice how all off these reasons have absolutely nothing to do with whether or not the people in question role-play or not?  It's a side-issue that has no bearing on whether or not the person is an RP God or a d00d-weasel.  Non-/anon and non-/role is just a way to be honest and open with people, especially your friends and guildmates. <p>Mosushi, Lizard Master of the Fish<br>
